				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{1}{2}\ln \left( {2\pi eV} \right)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M32"><mml:mrow><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mfrac><mml:mo>ln</mml:mo><mml:mfenced close=")" open="(" separators=""><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">π</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>V</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13104_2015_1786_Article_IEq14.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> as an attempt to linearize the relationship, using the 16 datasets from [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR15">15</xref>]. The only notably high correlation is found in the obesity dataset. The obesity data, however, contains a large number of missing values, rendering the high correlation less reliable. We conclude that standard statistical tests related to variance do not appear suitable for testing DSE.<table-wrap id="Tab1"><label>Table 1</label><caption><p>Correlations between SE and variance, and between SE and <inline-formula id="IEq18"><alternatives><tex-math id="M33">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
